 10  # Local equivalences
 11  
 12  This files defines equivalences between subsets of given types.
 13  An element `e` of `local_equiv α β` is made of two maps `e.to_fun` and `e.inv_fun` respectively
 14  from α to β and from  β to α (just like equivs), which are inverse to each other on the subsets
 15  `e.source` and `e.target` of respectively α and β.
 16  
 17  They are designed in particular to define charts on manifolds.
 18  
 19  The main functionality is `e.trans f`, which composes the two local equivalences by restricting
 20  the source and target to the maximal set where the composition makes sense.
 21  
 22  Contrary to equivs, we do not register the coercion to functions and we use explicitly to_fun and
 23  inv_fun: coercions create numerous unification problems for manifolds.
 24  
 25  ## Main definitions
 26  
 27  `equiv.to_local_equiv`: associating a local equiv to an equiv, with source = target = univ
 28  `local_equiv.symm`    : the inverse of a local equiv
 29  `local_equiv.trans`   : the composition of two local equivs
 30  `local_equiv.refl`    : the identity local equiv
 31  `local_equiv.of_set`  : the identity on a set `s`
 32  `eq_on_source`        : equivalence relation describing the "right" notion of equality for local
 33                          equivs (see below in implementation notes)
 34  
 35  ## Implementation notes
 36  
 37  There are at least three possible implementations of local equivalences:
 38  * equivs on subtypes
 39  * pairs of functions taking values in `option α` and `option β`, equal to none where the local
 40  equivalence is not defined
 41  * pairs of functions defined everywhere, keeping the source and target as additional data
 42  
 43  Each of these implementations has pros and cons.
 44  * When dealing with subtypes, one still need to define additional API for composition and
 45  restriction of domains. Checking that one always belongs to the right subtype makes things very
 46  tedious, and leads quickly to DTT hell (as the subtype `u ∩ v` is not the "same" as `v ∩ u`, for
 47  instance).
 48  * With option-valued functions, the composition is very neat (it is just the usual composition, and
 49  the domain is restricted automatically). These are implemented in `pequiv.lean`. For manifolds,
 50  where one wants to discuss thoroughly the smoothness of the maps, this creates however a lot of
 51  overhead as one would need to extend all classes of smoothness to option-valued maps.
 52  * The local_equiv version as explained above is easier to use for manifolds. The drawback is that
 53  there is extra useless data (the values of `to_fun` and `inv_fun` outside of `source` and `target`).
 54  In particular, the equality notion between local equivs is not "the right one", i.e., coinciding
 55  source and target and equality there. Moreover, there are no local equivs in this sense between
 56  an empty type and a nonempty type. Since empty types are not that useful, and since one almost never
 57  needs to talk about equal local equivs, this is not an issue in practice.
 58  Still, we introduce an equivalence relation `eq_on_source` that captures this right notion of
 59  equality, and show that many properties are invariant under this equivalence relation.
 60  -/

 66  /-- Local equivalence between subsets `source` and `target` of α and β respectively. The (global)
 67  maps `to_fun : α → β` and `inv_fun : β → α` map `source` to `target` and conversely, and are inverse
 68  to each other there. The values of `to_fun` outside of `source` and of `inv_fun` outside of `target`
 69  are irrelevant. -/
